comments.en: This is a vocabulary for DEDL version 0.1

abstract.value: The Data Ecosystem Description Language (DEDL) is an abstract language to describe concepts of data ecosystems, in which different participants (i.e., organizations and individuals) share data and generate value as the primary aim.

comment.en: Any identifiable object of a participant within the data ecosystem, e.g. a device or digital resource.
Application Programming Interface; a subclass of Interface representing a set of protocols allowing different software entities to communicate within a data ecosystem.
An AuthorizationArchitecture combining policy-based and token-based architecture
An authorization architecture using tokens (e.g., JWT)
An AuthorizationArchitecture where authorization relies on evaluating formalized policies.
A subclass of IdentityAndAccessManagement representing a structural framework that defines how authorization decisions are made and enforced.
Represents a network endpoint (URL) and its operational metadata for a Service.
An optional process that enables information or data to be found within a data ecosystem.
An infrastructure required for executing services within a data ecosystem, providing the necessary computing resources.
A service developed to address specific needs within a data ecosystem, often involving data processing or visualization.
A subclass of Interface enabling secure and standardized interaction within data spaces (i.e., specialized realizations of data ecosystems).
A subclass of Negotiating representing the process where data offers are made available to potential consumers.
Used for referencing between various classes
A subclass of Negotiating representing the process where potential data consumers request specific conditions for the use or access of data.
A subclass of IdentityAndAccessManagement representing a component responsible for managing digital identities, facilitating onboarding and offboarding processes in a data ecosystem.
A component responsible for documenting activities within a data ecosystem to ensure transparency.
A subclass of Participant representing a legal entity.
A subclass of Negotiation representing the concluding process between data providers and consumers  when a policy is accepted by both parties and a contract is formed.
A socio-technical system in which participants share and manage data and associated processes.
A subclass of PolicyStorage where data offers are stored, allowing participants in a data ecosystem to publish and manage their available datasets or services.
A sublcass of Publishing representing the process where participants make their data available to others in the data ecosystem.
A mandatory process that manages the creation of digital identities, enabling Participants to access a data ecosystem.
Base class defining various properties
Maintenance status indicating planned or ongoing maintenance.
Error status indicating a failure or problem.
Inactive status.
Active status.
Update status indicating an ongoing update.
Enumeration of possible status values for an element.
A stakeholder participating in or operating the data ecosystem (either an Individual or Organization).
Graphical User Interface; a subclass of Interface representing an interface through which users can visually interact with components of a data ecosystem.
A unique collection of attributes, credentials, or characteristics of an entity.
A protocol using a trusted third-party ticket-granting service for authentication.
Lightweight Directory Access Protocol, often used to manage authentication data in directories.
Security Assertion Markup Language (2.0), exchanging authentication and authorization data.
An authentication protocol relying on digital signatures for verification.
A web-based authentication protocol, encompassing flows like OAuth, SAML, or WebAuthn.
An authentication protocol leveraging cryptographic techniques to prove identity.
OpenID Connect, a simple identity layer built on OAuth 2.0 used for single sign-on.
A specification of the interactions or steps used to perform authentication.
A subclass of storage that stores the conditions under which access to resources in a data ecosystem is granted and how they may be used.
A subclass of Storage dedicated to string data within a data ecosystem.
A participant or component that assesses permissions and enforces authorization decisions.
A set of rules or guidelines that govern data usage, sharing, and access.
A policy specification language for security and management in distributed systems.
A digital rights management and usage rights framework which can serve as a policy language.
An ODRL-based language for expressing rights and usage constraints, common in news/media.
Open Digital Rights Language, commonly used to specify rights, constraints, and obligations.
An OASIS standard policy language for defining access control rules (XACML framework).

Access control policy language (ACP), a particular set of grammar, syntax rules (logical and mathematical), and operators which provides an abstraction-layer for access control policy specifications, see https://solid.github.io/authorization-panel/acp-specification/
A declarative policy language used with Open Policy Agent (OPA) to define fine-grained permissions.
A formal language for defining and expressing policies.
An Participant or component responsible for carrying out the authentication process.
A mandatory process that enables the exchange or transfer of data or other resources between Participants within a data ecosystem.
A component where various types of information are stored in a data ecosystem.
A series of operations or activities performed within the data ecosystem.
A Decision indicating that access is refused.
A Decision indicating that access is permitted.
An outcome regarding an authorization request, e.g. Allow or Deny.
A framework ensuring that only authorized Participants have access to a data ecosystem.
A subclass of Publishing representing the process that ensures datasets are stored securely, either centrally or decentrally, depending on the architecture of the data ecosystem.
An authentication factor using only one method of verification (e.g., a single password).
An authentication factor requiring two or more independent credentials.
An element used to verify the identity of a user or entity (e.g. password, token, biometrics).
An authentication process involving a three-part handshake or three-step verification.
A one-direction authentication process, typically from a client to a server.
A mutual authentication process where both parties verify each other's identity.
A procedure or sequence of steps that verify the identity of a user or entity.
A subclass of Transaction that represents the process that facilitates the transfer of data within a data ecosystem between Participants.
An authorization process where a client periodically checks the server for an access decision.
An authorization process involving negotiation or exchange of data before deciding access.
An authorization process where the server proactively notifies the client about decisions.
A method or set of steps determining if an entity may access a resource.
An element within a data ecosystem that contributes to its functionality and processes.
A subclass of DataEcosystemElement focused on technical components necessary for the operation of a data ecosystem.
A factor in the authentication risk context indicating the device used for login.
A factor in the authentication risk context representing physical or network location.
A context factor reflecting user behavioral patterns (e.g., keystroke dynamics).
A context factor referencing time-sensitive credentials or restrictions (e.g., OTPs).
Contextual attributes (time, location, device) that affect authentication risk levels.
An optional process where participants discuss and agree on policies leading to contracts within a data ecosystem.
An access point for participants to join and interact within a data ecosystem.
A mechanism through which participants in a data ecosystem exchange information and interact with each other.
An optional process that makes data discoverable and allows its findability through catalogs or metadata integration.
A subclass of Participant representing a legal person.
A  subclass of Transaction representing the process that enables third-party services execution to generate additional value from the managed data in a data ecosystem.
A subclass of PolicyStorage where concluded contracts are stored, ensuring that agreements between Participants are documented and accessible.
A mandatory process for removing participant identities from a data ecosystem ensuring compliance or voluntary exit.
Ontology-based Access Control focusing on contextual policy enforcement
Discretionary Access Control, where resource owners grant or deny permissions.
Role-based Access Control, assigning permissions to roles which are then assigned to users.
Attribute-based Access Control model, relying on attributes to define permissions.
Organization-based Access Control, focusing on roles and contexts within an organization.
Capability-based Access Control relying on tokens or 'capabilities' to grant permissions.
Mandatory Access Control, where policies are enforced by a central authority.
A conceptual framework defining how access to resources is managed, granted, and restricted.
Indicates the DataEcosystemElement belonging to a DataEcosystem.
Specifies the AuthorizationArchitecture used by an Authorizator.
Associates a DataEcosystem with a particular Process.
Authentication method or scheme (e.g., OAuth2, APIKey).
Associates a Service with an Endpoint resource that contains connection details (URL, method, auth, etc.).
Indicates the Participant using a TechnicalDataEcosystemElement (inverse of uses).
Links an Individual to an Organization.
HTTP method used to call the endpoint (e.g., GET, POST).
Links elements by specifying where data is received from.
Links an Authenticator to the authentication process used for identity verification.
Indicates if the data ecosystem consists of multiple data ecosystem
Indicates if the data ecosystem is part of another data ecosystem
Indicates the Process belonging to a DataEcosystem.
Specifies the AuthenticationProtocol an Authenticator follows.
Indicates the Entity belonging to a Participant.
Indicates the Participant operating a TechnicalDataEcosystemElement (inverse of operates).
Specifies an operator of a DataEcosystem.
Specifies a user of a TechnicalDataEcosystemElement.
Indicates whether a Participant has accepted the Gaia-X Terms and Conditions.
Specifies a participant within a DataEcosystem.
Links elements by specifying where data is sent.
Specifies an operator of a TechnicalDataEcosystemElement.
Indicates the authorization process followed by an Authorizator.
Associates a Participant with a particular Entity in the data ecosystem.
Indicates the AuthenticationFactor that an Authenticator uses.
Links an Entity to a Policy governing its usage or access rights.
Associates a Policy with its AccessControlModel to define and enforce resource access rules.
Associates a BBO:DataResource with an expected Property in another vocabulary (e.g. schema:legalName).
Associates TechnicalDataEcosystemElement with their current state-
Associates a BBO:DataResource with an expected Thing/Class in another vocabulary (e.g. vc:VerifiableCredential).
Indicates whether authentication is required to call the endpoint.
Indicates the Identity belonging to an Entity.
Specifies the PolicyLanguage used to express or encode a Policy.
Associates an Authenticator with contextual factors that influence authentication risk.
